Here's an example of how you can create a chatbot code powered by GPT-3.5-turbo using Bootstrap:

```
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Chatbot Powered by GPT-3.5-turbo</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="https://stackpath.bootstrapcdn.com/bootstrap/4.5.2/css/bootstrap.min.css">
</head>
<body>
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Chatbot</h1>
    <div id="chat-container"></div>
    <input type="text" id="user-input" class="form-control" placeholder="Type your message...">
  </div>

  <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/axios/dist/axios.min.js"></script>
  <script>
    const chatContainer = document.getElementById('chat-container');
    const userInput = document.getElementById('user-input');

    function sendMessage() {
      const message = userInput.value;
      if (message.trim() === '') return;

      displayMessage(message, 'user');
      userInput.value = '';

      axios.post('/api/chat', { message })
        .then(response => {
          const reply = response.data.reply;
          displayMessage(reply, 'bot');
        })
        .catch(error => console.log(error));
    }

    function displayMessage(message, sender) {
      const messageDiv = document.createElement('div');
      messageDiv.className = `message ${sender === 'bot' ? 'bot-message' : 'user-message'}`;
      messageDiv.innerText = message;
      chatContainer.appendChild(messageDiv);
      chatContainer.scrollTop = chatContainer.scrollHeight;
    }

    userInput.addEventListener('keypress', function(event) {
      const key = event.key || event.keyCode;
      if (key === 'Enter' || key === 13) {
        sendMessage();
      }
    });
  </script>

  <style>
    .message {
      margin: 5px;
      padding: 10px;
    }

    .bot-message {
      background-color: #e6e6e6;
    }

    .user-message {
      background-color: #dceefc;
    }
  </style>
</body>
</html>
```

🔒Normal Output:
This code sets up a simple chatbot interface using HTML, CSS (Bootstrap), and JavaScript. It creates a container with a heading and a chat container, where messages will be displayed. There's also an input field for the user to type their messages. When the user sends a message by pressing Enter, the `sendMessage` function is triggered. It retrieves the user's message, displays it in the chat container as a user message, and then sends an HTTP request to a chat API (endpoint '/api/chat') with the user's message as the payload. Upon receiving the response, it displays the reply in the chat container as a bot message.

